<div class="toptitle">
<h class="toptitle" style="font-family: lato, arial, sans-serif; font-size:500%; color: white;"><center> Greenspaces in Edinburgh as Carbon Stocks </center></h>
</div>
</div>
<br> <br> <br> <br>
<!---adding a break so there is a gap between bottom of image and beginning of text--->
<br>
<!---adding text and editing size, font, style, and position--->
<div style="background-color:whitesmoke; opacity: 0.96; height: 100%; padding-top: 20px; padding-bottom: 40px; margin-right: 60px; margin-left: 60px; padding-right: 40px; padding-left: 40px; border: 1px solid black;">
<p1 style="font-family:georgia, verdana, sans-serif;font-size:300%;"><center> <u>About the Project</u> </center></p1> <br></br>

<p2 style="font-family: Georgia, Verdana, sans-serif; line-height: 1.75;"><center>The importance of greenspace is widely researched and are increasingly considered in terms of environmental equality. The Capital Greenspace Project is a series of studies undertaken to investigate the significance of greenspaces on people's lives, communities, and avoiding environmental deprivation. In this project, carbon stock in particular is investigated. This type of research can therefore contribute to Central Scotland Green Network's vision of improving people's lives through environmental equality (CSGN, 2021) on the local level using Edinburgh City Council data. Greenspaces with carbon sequesters such as trees alleviate the global concern of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere (Wan et al. 2017), improve the 'heat island effect' and contribute to 'ecological, social, psychological and economic benefits' through afforestation (Shams et al. 2020). Environmental equality as a consideration for the value of greenspace is becoming ever more precendent (Walker. 2012; BBC. 2021; Floyd & Johnson. 2002; Frumkin. 2001). This research focused on the value of greenspaces in Edinburgh as carbon stocks. It then related these to deprivation, using the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation (SIMD). SIMD determines an areas deprivation based on: 'income, employment, education, health, access to services, crime and housing' (SIMD, 2020). The aims of the research were:
<ul>
<li>To understand the spatial pattern of high value carbon greenspaces in Edinburgh.</li>
<li>To determine the datazones which are both too far (> 1km) from a high value greenspace and are deprived (SIMD below 20% percentile).</li>
<li>To determine which greenspaces can be afforested to improve environmental deprivation.</li></ul>
<br>These aims were achieved with the following (simplified) methodology: </br>
<ol>
<li>The area and number of trees in each greenspace was calculated.</li>
<li>The carbon stock of each tree was calculated. </li>
<li>The carbon concentration (kg/m<sup>2</sup>) per greenspace was calculated.</li><br></br></ol> The greenspaces carbon value was then classified form high to low, and the SIMD bottom 20% percentile identified, in order to determine a 1km threshold from the high value carbon greenspaces (left hand map) and a 1km threshold from the bottom 20% percentile datazones (right hand map). A visual analysis was then performed to identify greenspaces for potential green development sites.</p2></center><br></br><br></br>
<center><img src="buffers.jpg" style="height:100%; width: 800px; padding-bottom: 40px;opacity:1;"></center>
<br>
</br>
<p3 style="font-family: Georgia, Verdana, sans-serif; line-height: 1.75;"><center> Use this website to learn about the project, the researchers, navigate the findings of this project using the <a href="https://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/~s2259785/findings.html">interactive map</a>, see our <a href="https://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/~s2259785/policy.html">policy recommendations</a> for Edinburgh City Council and discover what <a href="https://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/~s2259785/moreinfo.html">other research</a> within the Capital Greenspace Project found.</center></p3>
</div>
