<div style="background-color:whitesmoke; opacity: 0.96; height: 100%; padding-top: 20px; margin-right: 60px; margin-left: 60px; padding-right: 40px; padding-left: 40px; border: 1px solid black;">
<p5 style="font-family:georgia, verdana, sans-serif;font-size:300%"><center> <u>Data Quality</u></center></p5><br></br>
<div class="container">
<p6 style="padding-right: 20px; font-family: georgia, verdana, sans-serif; line-height: 1.75;"><center>A visual analysis of Landsat imagery was used to create polygons of misrepresented and omitted data. This can be seen in the figure to the right. The crossed polygons show greenspaces that were in the dataset, yet clearly contained more trees than shown from the data; thus, could be higher value greenspaces than calculated, and the dotted polygons show greenspaces found that were not in the data at all. <br><br> The input data used for this assessment was incomplete. The methodology hinged on two main datasets, the Trees and the Greenspaces. Although there were more complete tree datasets, we opted to remain with the more incomplete dataset due to its inclusion of key information about tree species, DBH and height, which was necessary for the calculation of carbon stock per tree. Unfortunately, many of the greenspaces near the far-deprived areas misrepresented the number of trees in the greenspace. Had a more complete tree dataset been available these far-deprived data zones may have differed. The outright omission of many greenspaces, particularly in the North-Western and Southern extents of Edinburgh, beg contemplation on the accuracy of the results and, as a consequence, our recommendations. <br><br> For example, even though the far Northwest corner of Edinburgh contains a far-deprived datazone shown through the buffers, it became clear upon further investigation that there were high-value greenspaces near this zone. However, these spaces were not counted in the data. Another issue with the data was that many of the greenspaces contained slivers or were split into separate polygons. We also had to go through all of our data to combine these polygons to gather accurate data on each individual greenspace.<br> <br> While thorough, this study has its limitations. The issue of data quality was one that was difficult to get around given time constraint and lack of funds. If given the time and resources, these findings may be more accurate. This study could have been improved with a more complete tree dataset to improve the accuracy of the findings for the value of carbon stocks in greenspaces in Edinburgh. </center></p6>
<img src="data.jpg" style="height:100%; width: 800px;">
</div>
