<div class="toptitle">
<h class="toptitle" style="font-family: lato, arial, sans-serif; font-size:400%; color: white; margin-left: 40px;">Policy Considerations</h>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<!---adding a break so there is a gap between bottom of image and beginning of text--->
<br>
<!---adding text and editing size, font, style, and position--->
<div style="background-color:whitesmoke; opacity: 0.96; height: 100%; padding-top: 20px; margin-right: 60px; margin-left: 60px; padding-right: 40px; padding-left: 40px; border: 1px solid black;">
<p1 style="font-family:georgia, verdana, sans-serif;font-size:300%;"><center><u>Afforestation Development Projects</u></center></p1> <br></br>
<div class="container">
<p2 style="padding-right: 20px; font-family: georgia, verdana, sans-serif; line-height: 1.75"><center>Having reviewed Landsat imagery, we propose several greenspace areas within the bottom 20% SIMD percentile that would benefit from afforestation, increasing these greenspaces carbon value so those living within a 1km threshold have access to a high value carbon greenspace; creating more environmental equality for these neighbourhoods. This aligns with Central Scotland Green Network's vision of enriching lives by improving the socio-spatial distribution of greenspaces (CSGN, 2022). The yellow polygons indicate the potential afforestation sites. Not all greenspace sites identified can be put forward, as some are private land (such as golf courses), which would require Edinburgh City Council to establish contact with private landowners. Public spaces that could potentially be afforested include Lochend Park (Restalrig/Jock's Lodge) and the sides of Ferry Road (Granton/Pilton). There are considerations for this policy proposal that need to be taken from a planning perspective (i.e. safety). Woodland greenspaces have been associated with increased crime and safety risks (Walker, 2012), as well as negative perceptions of greenspace access in more deprived areas leading to less frequent use (Jones et al, 2009). As a result, the involvement of citizens will be necessary in any afforestation planning undertaken. On-site feasibility assessments would also need to be conducted on the potential afforestation sites. Although afforestation would increase the carbon stock value of these greenspaces, the results would not be yielded immediately, as most trees native to Edinburgh require 30-50 years to mature (Trees in the City, 2021). Alternative methods for carbon sequesters could also be considered for this policies purpose such as green roofs, developing areas with higher species diversity, and plant density (Whittinghill et al, 2014).</center></p2>
<img src="policy.jpg" style="height:100%; width: 800px;">
</div>
<br>
</br>
</div>
<br>
</br>
<div style="background-color:whitesmoke; opacity: 0.96; height: 100%; padding-top: 20px; margin-right: 60px; margin-left: 60px; padding-right: 40px; padding-left: 40px; border: 1px solid black;">
<p3 style="font-family:georgia, verdana, sans-serif;font-size:300%"><center> <u>Environmental Equality in Multiple Deprivation Indexes</u></center></p3> <br></br>
<p4 style="font-family: georgia, verdana, sans-serif; line-height: 1.75;"><center>Environmental equality factors such as carbon value, pollution and flood risk are not currently considered within multiple deprivation indexes, or within census reporting or data. Our findings provide weight in the argument for their consideration, along with a re-evaluation of deprivation indexes around environmental considerations within socio-economic status. Previous research for deprivation implications between socio-economic status and environmental justice have been called to question before, for example in terms of exposure to environmental hazards (Briggs & Fecht, 2005). It has also been established that there is a relationship between lower socio-economic status and pejorative environmental effects (Shortt et al, 2011). For environmental factors to be considered within a deprivation index, concepts of 'environmental equality' need to be defined. These concepts could range from air pollution and fuel poverty to littering and (lack of) children's access to safe play areas (Pedersen, 2011). Other aspects of greenspace in Edinburgh that have been considered within the other Capital Greenspace Projects should also be considered for the afforestation on-site assessments and for environmental deprivation measures. More about these projects can be found in the <a href="https://www.geos.ed.ac.uk/~s2259785/moreinfo.html">More Information</a> page. </center></p4>
<br>
</br>
</div>
<br>
</br>
